06325nam a22008295i 9780814759530DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20062006nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147595307 a10.18574/nyu/97808147595302doi  a(DE-B1597)548307  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0040002bisacsh04a364.3086912097300aImmigration and Crime :bEthnicity, Race, and Violence /ced. by Ramiro Martinez, Jr., Abel Valenzuela, Jr. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Perspectives in Crime, Deviance, and Law ;v600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1 Coming to America: The Impact of the New Immigration on Crime -- tChapter 2 Rethinking the Chicago School of Criminology: A New Era of Immigration -- tChapter 3 Immigrant Assimilation and Crime: Generational Differences in Youth Violence in Chicago -- tChapter 4 Immigration and Incarceration: Patterns and Predictors of Imprisonment among First- and Second-Generation Young Adults -- tChapter 5 Immigration and Asian Homicide Patterns in Urban and Suburban San Diego -- tChapter 6 Delinquency and Acculturation in the Twenty-first Century: A Decade’s Change in a Vietnamese American Community -- tChapter 7 Beyond Conflict and Controversy: Blacks, Koreans, and Jews in Urban America -- tChapter 8 The “War on the Border” Criminalizing Immigrants and Militarizing the U.S.-Mexico Border -- tChapter 9 New Immigrants and Day Labor: The Potential for Violence -- tChapter 10 Multiple Disadvantages and Crime among Black Immigrants: Exploring Haitian Violence in Miami’s Communities -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe original essays in this much-needed collection broadly assess the contemporary patterns of crime as related to immigration, race, and ethnicity. Immigration and Crime covers both a variety of immigrant groups--mainly from Asia, the Caribbean, and Latin America--and a variety of topics including: victimization, racial conflict, juvenile delinquency, exposure to violence, homicide, drugs, gangs, and border violence.The volume provides important insights about past understandings of immigration and crime, many based on theories that have proven to be untrue or racially biased, as well as offering new scholarship on salient topics. Overall, the contributors argue that fears of immigrant crime are largely unfounded, as immigrants are themselves often more likely to be the victims of discrimination, stigmatization, and crime rather than the perpetrators.Contributors: Avraham Astor, Carl L. Bankston III, Robert J. Bursik, Jr., Roberto G. Gonzales, Sang Hea Kil, Golnaz Komaie, Jennifer Lee, Matthew T. Lee, Ramiro Martínez, Jr., Cecilia Menjívar, Jeffrey D. Morenoff, Charlie V. Morgan, Amie L. Nielsen, Rubén G. Rumbaut, Rosaura Tafoya-Estrada, Abel Valenzuela, Jr., Min Zhou.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aAstor, Avraham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBankston Iii, Carl L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBursik Jr., Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzales, Roberto G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJr., Abel Valenzuela,, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJr., Ramiro Martinez,, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKil, Sang Hea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomaie, Golnaz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Jennifer, 